Well, I missed the initial thread, so I may be missing the mark.  Here is
my 2 cents worth:

1.  A dual Pentium 100 is not a Pentium 200, period.  (Better or worse,
depending on the conditions).

2.  Under DOS, Windows, Windows95, Vanilla OS/2 and any other non-SMP
operating system a Dual-Pentium equals a Pentium 100 (i.e. you will never
get use of the second processor).

3.  Under a *GOOD* SMP operating system you can get anywhere from
%150-%210 the performance of a single Pentium 100.  For simplicity I will
not get into the argument of %210 performance... so lets say anywhere from
%150-%190.  How much you actually get depends on the OS, and applications.
A single single-threaded application will of course get no speedup, but
multi-threaded apps or multiple apps can take advantage of the added cpu
power.

4.  The software affects are as follows:

   A.  The OS must be a *GOOD* SMP OS.  If the OS supports SMP you
don't need to make any code changes to be able to run on such a box.
Multiple processes will benefit from the two processors, but *single-
threaded* applications, if timed on themselves, will not get a speedup (or
may slow down a little).  However, if more than one of these single
threaded applications is running you will get a good overall speedup (i.e.
2 single threaded jobs may complete in %60 of the time required for the
same 2 jobs on a uni-processor).

   B.  To take even better advantage of SMP the applications should be
written to use threads, together with a thread-supporting OS.  In that
case individual applications will see a good speedup as well.

